@node Intro "Introduction"
@{u}Introduction@{uu}

I wrote these few short scripts to provide a better level of interaction between Amiga Internet 
software. For example, have you ever noticed on Win3.11/Win95 systems the way that Web browsers and 
email clients call up the TCP stack and/or dialler. This is very handy as it saves time while online.

I may not have hit the nail right on the head, but I have come up with a simple but effective 
solution to the problem. I have written a few arexx scripts which can control different programs from
within another.

Here is a list of the included scripts, and what they do:

startnet.rexx  - Starts Miami if not present, and makes it go Online.  
stopnet.rexx   - Stops Miami, and makes it go Offline. 0
checkmail.rexx - Checks the mail in YAM from Ibrowse.
Connect        - Loads up Ibrowse and dials Miami as Ibrowse loads, this script has an icon and will 
                 be executed automatically when double-clicked.

I am not an arexx expert, but these scripts do what I need them to do. I uploaded these to the Aminet 
mainly because it is very handy to have the TCP stack initiated when a Web Browser is loaded, and I 
am fairly sure that other people would like this idea. I would appreciate any comments, feedback or 
suggestions about these scripts. Please contact @{"me" link author} if you do.  

@endnode
@node req "Requirements"
@{u}Requirements@{uu}

Here is a list of the requirements needed to run these scripts:

-Miami TCP/IP 
-IBrowse 
-YAM 1.3.4, may work on earlier versions, but has not been tested. 
-Rexxmast running in the background.
-About 4Mb of RAM, to run all the needed software.
-Harddrive is essential :-)
-A little knowledge on the Shell woyld be handy.
-NewIcons required for the "Connect" icon. (This is not essential but makes Workbench look great :-)

See the @{"Usage" link use} section on changing these scripts to suit your own setup/software. This 
may increase or decrease the RAM needed. 
@endnode

@node install "Installation"
@{uu}Installation@{uu}

Unfortunately, I am not very good at writing installer scripts, I will provide step by step 
instructions here instead, don`t worry there is nothing too complicated in the installation.

@{b}N.B.@{ub} Installation instructions do not apply to the script "Connect"

1. If it doesn`t exist, create a directory "rexx" in the Ibrowse directory.
   e.g. type "makedir work:Ibrowse/rexx" into a shell, without quotes.
2. Copy the contents of the rexx directory from this archive to the rexx directory in Ibrowse.
3. To make these scripts easy to access, you must edit the General Preferences in Ibrowse as follows:
  1.Go to "General" in the Preferences menu in Ibrowse.
  2.Go to the Rexx section.
  3.Click on "Add", type in the name you want to appear in the Rexx menu of Ibrowse in the "Name:" box.
  4.To specify the Macro, click the file requester button and select "rexx", followed by the needed 
    script. For an explanation of the script names, refer to the @{"Introduction" link Intro}.
  5.Go to OK and save the settings.
4. If you get the error message "rx: Unknown command
						   rx failed returncode 10" you should copy the "rx" file (sys:rexxc/rx) 
   to the Ibrowse directory. This should solve the problem.
5. If you get an error saying something like "rexxmast not running", you need to run rexxmast, the 
   best thing to do is insert the following line in your user-startup (in S:)
														"run >nil: rexxmast"		 

@{b}Installing the "Connect" script@{ub}	

This is the script used to load the TCP stack and Web Browser at the same time. It is basically a 
script with an icon (if you only see a small dot this because it is a NewIcon) that can execute the 
script. You may place this icon anywhere on your HD. Just make sure that "rx" is somewhere in your 
path (it`s normally in sys:rexxc/). That`s all there is to it! 

This is not essential or even needed, but I think it looks nicer to leave the icon out on the desktop
for easy and instant access, not to mention show off to PeeCee owning, Microsoft controlled zombies 
that you can connect to the `Net with a click of a mouse button on the Amiga aswell. 

@endnode
@node use "Usage"
@{u}Usage@{uu}

If you are using Miami/Ibrowse/YAM, then usage is fairly simple, you can just double click on the 
Connect icon to launch it, and the other scripts can be accessed from the Ibrowse Rexx menu, if you 
installed the scripts as described in @{"Installation" link install}.

However, you may need to change the paths of the programs specified in the scripts, you can do this 
in any text editor such as ed. E.g. "ed work:Ibrowse/rexx/startnet.rexx". If the path(s) in this file 
do not correspond to your own setup, change the path as required. Try this procedure for any script 
you are having trouble with. I am hoping to do an Installer script which could do this with less 
hassle. 

If you are using different programs you will have to change the required paths and addresses in the 
script, for this an understanding of Arexx of is needed. I also hope to be able to do an Installer 
script which covers this.

Email @{"me" link author} if you have any problems.  
@endnode
